SIMPLE: hoist
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hoist
<hw>Hoist</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hoisted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hoisting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hoise</ets>,
<ets>hyse</ets>, OD. <ets>hyssen</ets>, D. <ets>hijshen</ets>; akin to
LG. <ets>hissen</ets>, Dan. <ets>hisse</ets>, Sw.
<ets>hissa</ets>.]</ety> <def>To raise; to lift; to elevate; esp., to
raise or lift to a desired elevation, by means of tackle, as a sail, a
flag, a heavy package or weight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They land my goods, and <qex>hoist</qex> my flying sails.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hoisting</qex> him into his father's throne.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hoisting engine</b></col>, <cd>a steam engine for
operating a hoist.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoist</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hoist
<hw>Hoist</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That by which anything is
hoisted; the apparatus for lifting goods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of hoisting; a lift.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The perpendicular
height of a flag, as opposed to the <xex>fly</xex>, or horizontal length
when flying from a staff.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The height of a
fore-and-aft sail next the mast or stay.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hoist bridge</b></col>, <cd>a drawbridge that is lifted
instead of being swung or drawn aside.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoist</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hoist
<hw>Hoist</hw>, <pos>p. p.</pos> <def>Hoisted.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is the sport to have the enginer⟦br⟧
<qex>Hoist</qex> with his own petar.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hoistaway</ent>⟦br⟧
